<br>
Canadian/US universities tend to have low admission standards, and then weed out people as they move up (my college, for example, had a 45% drop-out rate between freshman and senior years).<br>
Also, Canadian/US universities (and employers afterward) tend to keep careful track of your rank within the school.  <br>
<br>
Japanese universities, on the other hand, are notorious for having incredibly difficult entrance exams, followed by 4 years of party-party-party.  Class rank, AFAIK, isn't something folks care about much.<br>
<br>
So, if you're planning to apply to a Japanese university, expect a VERY VERY tough entrance exam.<br>
<br>
----<br>
Tokyo University (nicknamed to-dai, rhymes with &quot;toad's eyes&quot;) is possibly the toughest university in Japan... approximately equal to MacGill in Canada or Harvard in America.  So, I'm pretty surprised to hear you mention To-dai.  Are your grades THAT good ?<br>
<br>
----<br>
Others in this thread have said that many Universities offer classes in English, and may have low &quot;japanese-proficiency&quot; standards for admission.<br>
I haven't heard this... first I've heard of it... but I'd tend to expect that a student admitted to those classes would be steered toward Japanese language and literature courses, with a smattering of liberal-arts-type classes conducted in English.  I would NOT expect (though I'm guessin' / talkin' outta mah arse, here (!)) to find civil engineering or other hard-science courses to be conducted in English.<br>
<br>
Generally, the university-general-admissions standard for Japanese proficiency is passing the LEVEL 2 version of the JLPT test.  That means knowing alot of grammar, and knowledge of 1,000 kanji, which equates to basic literacy. JLPT stands for Japanese Language Proficiency Test.  The test is offered once yearly, in December.<br>
<br>
These standards probably do NOT apply to foreign students wishing to learn Japanese.  See above comments about probable restrictions on what courses you could take, without having passed the JLPT level-2 test.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=digitalforever@polykarbonbbs>DigitalForever</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Pre-Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(11/24/03 1:18 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://p084.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1278.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: To-dai and Japanese colleges in general</span><hr size=1> lol... I probably won't get into To-Dai then... Thanks for the info, what about Keio? What I am aiming for is to take their Japanese Language course so I am profecient enough in Japanese to take courses gearing towards Civil Engineering... etc... Is that possible? As stupid as this sounds but I am not entirely sure about the differences in Degree Programs, Undergraduate Programs, Graduate Programs, and Doctoral Programs( I do understand the Japanese Language program... :P) Please don't hate me for asking... <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   Thanks for the info SethNess!<br>
