<br>
However, I would urge you to explore the individual university websites on your own (I would do it for you, but I don't have enough time).  Almost all of them have information for international students.<br>
<br>
For example, here is Waseda's admission requirements for &quot;normal&quot; undergraduate degree study:<br>
<br>
(taken from <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.waseda.ac.jp/eng/admission/eligibility.html" target="top">the waseda website</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->)<br>
<br>
1. To be eligible for admission to the undergraduate schools, applicants must have completed a 12-year course of elementary and secondary education, i.e. to be graduates of an accredited secondary school abroad, or to <br>
possess equivalent or superior credentials<br>
<br>
<br>
2. Applicants must hold a visa for the purpose of studying as a college student (ryugaku) in a university or as a pre-college students (shugaku), or must hold a visa other than the above-mentioned visas, but which can be changed <br>
to a college student visa (ryugaku visa) after enrollment in the university.<br>
<br>
<br>
3. Admission is limited to those taking the EJU for this academic year, to be administered by AIEJ on Sunday, November 17, 2002. Applicants to the School of Science and Engineering should take the EJU on Sunday, June 16, 2002. Notes:  EJU (Examination for Japanese University Admission for International Students); <br>
AIEJ (The Association of International Education, Japan) <br>
<br>
It seems you will need to take the EJU (see above) in order to be admitted as a &quot;regular&quot; degree seeking student.  You can find out more about it <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.aiej.or.jp/examination/efjuafis_e.html" target="top">here</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->, but basically you're gonna need to be able to pass the 2nd level of the proficiency exam as Sethness said.<br>
<br>
As for their special &quot;international division&quot; (i.e. no japanese required), it doesn't seem like it is a degree granting program, (i.e. 1 yr only?) but you're gonna have to look it up on your own.  As seth said, this is aimed more at art/culture/language studies.  Civil engineering is most definitely reserved for &quot;normal&quot; undergraduate courses.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.waseda.ac.jp/cie/international/IDP.html" target="top">waseda international division link</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
Of course, you could always start out in the international division and work your way into &quot;regular degree courses&quot; as your japanese improves, but realistically speaking, it's highly unlikely your japanese will improve to the point that you can take regular university classes in such a difficult subject in just one or two years.  Of course, if you can already speak japanese now, that's a different subject...<br>
<br>
In case you're wondering why I keep harping on Waseda, it's only because I happened to have looked up some info on it already, as they <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>do</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> offer <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>graduate</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> courses taught primarily in english (i.e. masters programs conducted mainly in english).  A friend of mine (can't speak japanese) is taking some sort of economic/finance masters program there next year.  So it is possible, but only for graduate students (but check the website to see about undergrad).  If nothing else, call to all the different schools and just ask your questions directly.<br>
<br>
As far as Keio, it's probably the 2nd highest ranked school in Japan, behind Tokyo University.  Waseda, Kyoto and Sophia are probably around 3rd, 4th and 5th, in that order (in my informal survey).  One good thing I will mention is that Sophia (Jyouchi Daigaku) has a very good &quot;international campus&quot; and I believe it has degree granting undergraduate programs taught entirely in english.  And as my girlfriend will attest, Sophia girls have a reputation for being pretty, smart <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>and</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> quite good at english.  (i agree!) <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->    So you might want to check it out.<br>
<br>
About your question regarding nyugaku shiken (entrance exams) - I'm Not Sure. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   I know there are different exams depending on if you're applying to national universities (Tokyo, Kyoto) or private universities (Waseda, Keio, Sophia).  Furthermore, some universities have two exams - they use the national examination (which everyone has to take) and their own individual exam (only for that school).  However, in the case of international students, you might only have to take the EJU (mentioned above), though I'm not sure.  For Todai, you'll probably have to take the same exam as everyone else <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Finally, about the differences in programs.  Don't be ashamed, it's not a stupid question!  I never knew until my guidance counselor finally sat me down waaaaaay back in my senior year of HS and explained it to me. <br>
<br>
1. &quot;degree programs&quot; usually means &quot;undergraduate&quot; degree programs.  This means any kind of program (usually four years) for which you complete a core set of required courses and are granted an official &quot;degree&quot; from the university. Usually this is either a B.S. (bachelor of Science) or B.A. (bachelor of arts) - these are essentially identical and are what you get when you &quot;graduate from college&quot;.  BS's are offered to people who study hard sciences, while BA's are reserved for things like literature, art, etc. (i.e liberal arts).  It doesn't mean much - in my university you could get either a B.S. or a B.A. in political science, either of which is the same.  <br>
<br>
This can also refer to &quot;associate degrees&quot; which are 2 year degrees granted by technical colleges and some community colleges.  Generally these are not looked upon as favorably as a B.S./B.A.  And hopefully Seth can correct me, but I'm not sure if these count towards the work visa requirements for japan (i think they do, though).<br>
<br>
2. Graduate programs.  This is a programmed course of study you take <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>after</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> you complete your undergrad study (and get your bachelors degree/whatever).  Usually this is about 2-3 years and will grant you a &quot;Masters degree&quot; (M.S./M.A./M.B.A/etc. depending on your field).  The study is more difficult and you usually end up doing research with a supervising professor.  You will generally try and get published (especially in the hard sciences) and will most likely have to write a masters thesis that will go on file in national archives somewhere.  M.A.s in many fields greatly improve your marketability, though in some fields (i.e. literature/social science, etc. they may not make too large of a difference).<br>
<br>
3. Doctoral programs.  These are programs that result in your receiving a doctoral degree, generally a &quot;doctor of philosophy&quot; (Ph.D.) (don't worry about the name - you'll still get a Ph.D. even if you are studying nuclear physics.  essentially any doctoral program that isn't an M.D. or O.D. (doctor of osteopathy?  same as M.D.) program will give you a Ph.D.).  These programs take <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>another</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->2~3 years on top of the masters study.  You will definitely be doing lots of research, publish a ton, and will have to write and *defend* a doctoral thesis.  After it is accepted and you have completed your studies to the satisfaction of your Ph.D. committee members, you will be granted your doctoral degree.  Congratulations, you are now (theoretically, at least) in possession of the highest academic degree available.  You should (again, theoretically) expect to be highly marketable, be able to become a professor, provide soundbites for news programs and get very very filthy rich.    Or so the theory goes <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
