<br>
First of all, I asked around a bit.  The &quot;top&quot; colleges in Japan are (roughly in this order):<br>
Tokyo University (Todai)<br>
Keio University *<br>
Kyoto University (Kyodai)<br>
Waseda University *<br>
Osaka University (Handai)<br>
Sophia University (Jyochi) *<br>
Nagoya University (Nagoyadai)<br>
<br>
Universities marked with an * are private, the rest are national universities.  Please note this is just a rough list, and things can get a bit muddled, especially towards the bottom.  And just as back home, rankings are not as important as other factors - appropriate courses of study, comfortable environments, etc.<br>
<br>
Tuition at national universities ranges around 500,000 yen/year (~$4200 US) while private universities are more around the 1,000,000 yen/year range (~$8400 US), though this may be different by school and also for international students.<br>
<br>
The procedure for the much vaunted &quot;university entrance exams&quot; is as follows.<br>
<br>
There are two exams (generally): a 'national' exam (everyone has to take it) and an 'individual' exam which differs according to the school you want to enter.<br>
<br>
The national exam (&quot;SENTA shiken&quot;)is usually comprised of 8 subjects which differ according to the school you want to enter and the subject you want to study.  So for example, those of you wanting to enter a medical programs might be taking exam subjects such as biology, chemstry or physics, while those of you interested in sociology (for example) might take subjects like english, japanese and math.  While people will take different combinations of subjects, everyone's &quot;math&quot; section (for example) will be the same, regardless of where they're going (provided they take math).  You don't get a choice in what subjects you will test on - the university will inform you of that.<br>
<br>
The maximum score is 800 (each subject is worth 100 points).  <br>
<br>
The second exam (&quot;NIJI shiken&quot;) comes later.  Again, you don't get a choice in subject matter, but this time there are only 2~3 subjects.  This test is different for every university, so the exam (and contents of individual subjects) for an exam to get into Todai is different than that to get into Sophia.  You don't receive a &quot;score&quot; for the second exam, but only a ranking relative to other test takers.  It is from this ranking, among other information (including the results of your first exam) that determine whether you will be accepted or not.<br>
<br>
There is an important point I should mention. You don't automatically get to take the second exam!  There is a cutoff (&quot;ashikiri&quot;) for the first exam which you have to meet.  For example, in the case of Todai, if you only receive 400 points on the first exam, you will not be permitted to take the second exam at all!  (this is not the actual cutoff - in reality it's probably much higher)<br>
<br>
Furthermore, the two exams are not weighted equally.  In the case of Todai, your first exam results only count ~50%, so the results of the second exam (and consequently your ranking) are <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>extremely</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> important.  Now you can see why things are so competitive!<br>
<br>
That having been said, foreigners occasionally get exempted from these exams and are required to take the EJU (see above) instead.  But this is not always the case!  While many of the schools above may offer special &quot;international courses&quot; or institutes that cater to foreigners, often (and this is especially true of the most prestigious schools) foreigners seeking admission to any part of the university other than those 'special foreigner courses' (i.e. admission as a regular degree seeking student) are required to take the exact same entrance exams as Japanese students!  Needless to say, there are few exemptions provided for the language barrier (at keio, for example, you're allowed to bring a paper dictionary, but that's it).<br>
<br>
Of course, since ESID (&quot;every situation is different&quot;) it would behoove you to look up individual information by yourselves.  Here are the links to some of the universities mentioned above (english language page) - clicking on &quot;international&quot; or &quot;admissions&quot; will generally point you in the right direction.<br>
