ertainly need to pass the same entrance exam (or the foreigner's equivelant, see above) as japanese students.<br>
<br>
Are you sure you wouldn't rather consider an exchange program?  one or two years abroad, but receiving your degree from an american institution might be a wise course to consider, depending on your field of study.  I think I mentioned this to you before in another post, but generally japanese universities are far less demanding than their american counterparts.  Unless you're planning study at one of the &quot;ichi-ryu&quot; (top ranked) schools, you would almost certainly be better off with a BS/BA from an american university, in terms of practical knowledge gained and relative marketability of your degree.<br>
<br>
I don't know anyone who has ever &quot;transferred&quot; to a Japanese university from a US one before, so you're going to have to take this issue up with the university of your choice directly.  I suggest you contact them over the phone and just ask them, as that would be the quickest and clearest way to get the specific information you're looking for.<br>
<br>
I can't really recommend one course of action over the other - I think this is sort of up to you.  Some questions which I think may be really helpful for you to consider in making this decision are:<br>
1. what do you want to accomplish in the future?<br>
2. what do you want to study in college?<br>
3. what do you want to accomplish in japan?<br>
4. what are the practical reasons for you wanting to study in japan?<br>
for this last two, I think you also need to ask:<br>
<br>
5. is it possible to accomplish these japan goals simply by studying abroad? I.E. what is the *definitive* reasons why you *have* to enter, study and graduate from a Japanese university rather than an american one.<br>
<br>
Entering and graduating from a foreign university is a difficult undertaking.  There are economic, cultural and language issues to consider, not to mention a host of minutia that need to be dealt with such as visa issues, understanding lectures completely, finding legal work, etc. etc.  This is not to discourage you of course!  I think that studying abroad is truely a precious experience.  <br>
<br>
I think that if you can provide good answers for these questions, it may go a long way towards helping you decide what to do in the future, whether to enter japanese university directly, attempt to transfer two years in, or perhaps just do a study abroad.<br>
<br>
I hope this helps. <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em><!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="font-size:xx-small;">Mamonaku. 11ban sen ni  Panda densha ga mairimasu. </span><!--EZCODE FONT END--> <!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END--> <!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="font-size:xx-small;">Abunai desu kara, kiiro no sen no uchigawa made osagarikudasai.</span><!--EZCODE FONT END-->  </em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> </strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
